    page: 3,
    title: "The Kalman Filter: A Recursive Estimator for Object Dynamics",
    content: "The Kalman filter is not a tracking algorithm. It is a general-purpose recursive state estimator that happens to be extremely useful for tracking. Understanding this distinction matters because the Kalman filter's properties, including its assumptions, limitations, and failure modes, derive from estimation theory, not from computer vision.\n\nA state estimator maintains an internal model of a system's condition based on incomplete and noisy observations. The system in this case is a moving object. The state includes everything the tracker needs to know about the object: its position, its size, and its velocity. The observation is the bounding box produced by the detector, which is a noisy measurement of the object's true position and size.\n\nThe Kalman filter models the relationship between consecutive states using a state transition equation. In DeepSORT, this equation implements a constant-velocity assumption: the object's position at time t+1 equals its position at time t plus its velocity times the time interval. The velocity itself remains constant between frames. This is expressed mathematically as a linear system where the state vector is multiplied by a transition matrix that shifts positions by the corresponding velocities.\n\nThe state vector in DeepSORT has eight dimensions. Four dimensions describe the bounding box: horizontal center (u), vertical center (v), aspect ratio (a), and height (h). The remaining four dimensions describe the rates of change of these quantities: du/dt, dv/dt, da/dt, and dh/dt. This parameterization captures both where the object is and how it is changing.\n\nAlongside the state vector, the filter maintains a covariance matrix that quantifies the uncertainty in each state dimension and the correlations between dimensions. A newly initialized track has small position uncertainty (the detector just measured it) but large velocity uncertainty (velocity must be inferred from multiple measurements). As more frames are processed, the velocity estimate becomes more precise and the covariance shrinks.\n\nThe predict step projects both the state and the covariance forward by one time step. The state transitions according to the motion model. The covariance grows by an amount determined by the process noise, which represents the degree to which the constant-velocity assumption is violated. High process noise tells the filter to expect unpredictable motion and trust future measurements more. Low process noise tells the filter to expect smooth motion and rely more on its own predictions.\n\nThe update step incorporates a new detector measurement to refine the state estimate. The Kalman gain, computed from the ratio of the prediction uncertainty to the measurement uncertainty, determines how much the state shifts toward the measurement. When the prediction is uncertain (large covariance) and the measurement is precise (small detector noise), the gain is high and the state jumps toward the measurement. When the prediction is confident and the measurement is noisy, the gain is low and the state barely changes.\n\nDuring occlusion, no update step occurs. The filter simply predicts forward, and the covariance grows with each frame. After several frames of prediction without update, the position estimate has degraded significantly. The Mahalanobis distance metric used for association accounts for this growing uncertainty: it is more forgiving of spatial mismatches when the covariance is large, preventing spurious track deletions during occlusion.\n\nThe constant-velocity assumption is both the strength and the weakness of the Kalman filter in DeepSORT. It works well for the vast majority of tracking scenarios: vehicles cruising on highways, pedestrians walking at steady pace, boats motoring across harbors. It fails during rapid acceleration, sharp turns, and sudden stops. For drone applications where monitored objects frequently change speed and direction, increasing the process noise parameter allows the filter to adapt more quickly at the cost of less smooth trajectories.\n\nAn extended Kalman filter or unscented Kalman filter could model nonlinear dynamics more accurately, but the additional computational cost is rarely justified for bounding box tracking where the dominant source of error is the detector itself, not the motion model.",
